{
  "version": 2,
  "name": "Particle Text",
  "description": "Particle Text — text baked into the FluidSim2D force field as a curl-rotated gradient. Decomposed from the legacy `ParticleTextGenerator` Rust struct, but with a fundamentally different topology: rather than seeding particles AT bright text texels and letting them dissipate (the legacy approach), the text bitmap is converted to a vec2 force field that pushes particles ALONG the glyph edges every frame. Particles seed from FluidSim2D's standard uniform grid; the text influence is continuous — glyphs emerge as standing waves in the flow rather than discrete formations that dissolve.\n\nTopology delta vs FluidSim2D: a parallel text-force branch is added between `fluid_gradient_rotate.force` and the field blurs. The branch is `node.render_text → gaussian_blur H+V (radius 8 px, softens the gradient so it isn't single-texel spiky) → gradient_central_diff (R channel) → rotate_vec2_90 (CCW: turns the attract-into-glyph gradient into a perpendicular curl-along-edge flow, divergence-free) → gain (driven by outer-card text_strength) → blend Add → field_blur_h → field_blur_v → fluid_simulate.field`. All other FluidSim2D plumbing (clip-trigger modes, scatter, resolve, density chain, tone-map) is preserved verbatim.\n\nNew outer-card params on top of the FluidSim2D surface: text (string), fontFamily (string), text_size (font height as a fraction of output height, 0.05..1.0, default 0.25), text_strength (gain on the text-derived force, 0..20, default 4.0). The legacy ParticleText `text_size` slider keeps its meaning. The legacy `text` + `fontFamily` strings flow through `stringBindings` into `node.render_text` the same way `Text.json` wires them.\n\nDeparture from the legacy visual: particles never \"form the text and dissolve\" — the text is a persistent attractor / repeller depending on local flow direction. Best results with `text_strength` 3–8 and `text_size` 0.3–0.6, against the FluidSim2D defaults. Increase `feather` for chunkier glyph trails; increase `count_m` to fill the text shape more densely.",
